---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
import DemoVideo from '../../components/DemoVideo.astro';
import FAQSection from '../../components/FAQSection.astro';
import BlogPostFooter from '../../components/BlogPostFooter.astro';
import { config } from '../../config';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is a lien waiver in construction?',
    answer:
      "A lien waiver is a legal document signed by a contractor or subcontractor that waives the right to file a mechanics lien against a property for a specified amount. GCs and owners collect them as proof that the payment chain is clean — that you won't place a lien claim on the property for the amounts paid. There are four standard types: conditional progress, unconditional progress, conditional final, and unconditional final.",
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the difference between a conditional and unconditional lien waiver?',
    answer:
      "A conditional waiver only takes effect if and when payment actually clears — your lien rights are protected if the check bounces or never arrives. An unconditional waiver takes effect the moment you sign it, regardless of whether you've been paid. Conditional waivers are safe to sign concurrent with payment; unconditional waivers should only be signed after funds have cleared your account.",
  },
  {
    question: 'Can a GC require me to sign an unconditional waiver before I get paid?',
    answer:
      "A GC can ask, but this creates real risk for the sub. If you sign an unconditional waiver and payment never comes, you've waived your lien rights for that amount — making collections much harder. The industry standard is to exchange a conditional progress waiver at the time of payment and convert to unconditional once funds clear. Several states limit a GC's ability to require unconditional waivers before payment; check the applicable state statute for the project's location.",
  },
  {
    question: 'Do progress lien waivers cover my retainage?',
    answer:
      "A properly drafted progress lien waiver explicitly carves out withheld retainage — it covers only the amount paid that period, not the portion held back. A final unconditional lien waiver, once signed, covers the full contract amount including retainage. Don't sign a final unconditional waiver until you've confirmed the complete payment, including retainage, has cleared your account.",
  },
  {
    question: 'Are lien waiver forms standardized across states?',
    answer:
      'Several states — California and Arizona among the most widely cited — mandate specific statutory lien waiver forms. Using a non-compliant form in those states can leave the waiver invalid or create grounds for dispute. In states without mandatory forms, the language in whatever document you sign is what governs, so read the scope, the dollar amount, and whether retainage is excluded before signing anything unconditional.',
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Construction Lien Waivers: Conditional vs. Unconditional | BuildWorkPro"
  description="The four types of construction lien waivers, when to sign them, and why the conditional vs. unconditional distinction matters for every pay app you submit."
>
  <Header />
  <main class="pt-32 pb-20">
    <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="mb-12">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-brand-600 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Blog</p>
        <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold text-slate-900 tracking-tight leading-tight">
          Construction Lien Waivers Explained: Conditional vs. Unconditional
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-slate-400">Published June 23, 2026 · 7 min read</p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tight prose-a:text-brand-600"
      >
        <p>
          Lien waivers don't come with much explanation the first time you sign one. Your GC sends a
          form with the check, you sign it, and the job moves on. But a lien waiver is a legal
          document that gives up a property right — and what kind you sign, and when, determines
          whether you're protected or exposed if payment doesn't clear.
        </p>
        <p>
          This guide explains the four types of construction lien waivers, what the conditional vs.
          unconditional distinction actually means, and when each type comes up in the pay
          application and closeout process.
        </p>

        <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-100 p-6 not-prose my-8">
          <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">Key takeaways</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-600 list-disc pl-5">
            <li>
              There are four standard types: conditional progress, unconditional progress,
              conditional final, and unconditional final.
            </li>
            <li>
              Conditional waivers only take effect when payment clears — safe to sign concurrent
              with payment.
            </li>
            <li>
              Unconditional waivers take effect immediately upon signing — never sign one until
              funds are confirmed in your account.
            </li>
            <li>
              Progress waivers cover a specific billing period; final waivers cover the full
              contract including retainage.
            </li>
            <li>
              Several states mandate statutory forms — using a non-compliant form can make the
              waiver invalid.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>What is a construction lien waiver?</h2>
        <p>
          A mechanics lien is one of the most effective collection tools available to
          subcontractors. When a sub isn't paid for work performed, a mechanics lien attaches to the
          property title and can prevent the owner from selling or refinancing until the debt is
          resolved. That leverage is exactly why owners and GCs require a waiver of it with every
          payment.
        </p>
        <p>
          A lien waiver is a signed document stating that in exchange for receiving — or upon
          receiving — a specified payment, you're giving up your lien rights for that amount. The GC
          or owner collects it as evidence that the payment chain is clean for amounts paid to date.
        </p>
        <p>
          Lien waivers appear at two points on any project: during progress billing (one waiver per
          pay application period) and at closeout (a final waiver covering the full contract). The
          conditional vs. unconditional distinction determines how much risk you accept when you
          sign.
        </p>

        <h2>The four types of lien waivers</h2>
        <p>
          Construction lien waivers fall into a two-by-two grid: conditional or unconditional, and
          progress or final. Each combination has a different purpose and a different risk profile.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Conditional progress waiver</strong> — covers the current billing period; takes effect
            only when that period's payment clears. The standard waiver to exchange with each pay application.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Unconditional progress waiver</strong> — covers the current billing period; takes
            effect upon signing. Only sign after confirming that period's payment is in your account.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Conditional final waiver</strong> — covers the full contract including retainage;
            takes effect when final payment clears. Appropriate to sign when submitting your final pay
            application, while you're waiting on the last check.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Unconditional final waiver</strong> — covers the full contract including retainage;
            takes effect upon signing. Sign only after every dollar, including withheld retainage, has
            cleared.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Conditional vs. unconditional: why the distinction matters</h2>
        <p>
          This is the most important distinction for subcontractors, and it's worth understanding
          precisely.
        </p>
        <p>
          A <strong>conditional lien waiver</strong> is contingent on payment being received. The legal
          effect is suspended until the condition — receipt of the stated payment — is satisfied. If the
          check bounces, the wire doesn't arrive, or the GC defaults, the waiver never becomes effective
          and your lien rights are intact. You can sign a conditional waiver at the same time you hand
          over your{' '}
          <a href="/features/pay-applications/">pay application</a> — before the money arrives — without
          taking on meaningful risk.
        </p>
        <p>
          An <strong>unconditional lien waiver</strong> takes effect the moment you sign it. It doesn't
          matter whether payment arrived, bounced, or was never sent. Once signed, you've waived your
          lien rights for the stated amount with no conditions attached. Signing an unconditional waiver
          before payment has cleared your account is a real exposure: if the GC or owner defaults after
          you've signed, you've given up your primary collection leverage.
        </p>
        <p>
          The right sequence: sign a <em>conditional</em> waiver when payment is issued or concurrent
          with submitting your pay app, then sign the <em>unconditional</em> version only after you've
          confirmed the funds are in your account.
        </p>

        <h2>Progress waivers vs. final waivers</h2>
        <p>
          The progress vs. final dimension covers what portion of the contract the waiver applies
          to.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Progress lien waivers</strong> cover a specific billing period — the dates and amount
          on that period's pay application. A conditional progress waiver is what you'll sign most often:
          one per pay app, covering only the amount billed in that period. Critically, a well-drafted
          progress waiver explicitly excludes withheld retainage. It does not waive your rights for the
          retained amount, for future periods, or for any disputed work.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Final lien waivers</strong> cover the complete contract, including all retainage. A
          conditional final waiver is appropriate once you've submitted your final pay application and
          are waiting on the full remaining balance. An unconditional final waiver should only be signed
          after you've confirmed every dollar — including the final retainage check — has cleared your
          account.
        </p>
        <p>
          Before signing any waiver, verify the stated amount matches what you actually billed for
          that period, and check whether retainage is explicitly carved out on progress waivers.
          These details control what you're giving up.
        </p>

        <h2>When lien waivers come up in the pay application process</h2>
        <p>
          On most projects the flow looks like this: you submit your pay application for the period,
          the GC processes it, and payment arrives alongside a conditional progress lien waiver for
          you to sign. Some GCs send the waiver in advance and expect you to return it before they
          cut the check; others send both at the same time. Either way, the key question is whether
          the form is conditional or unconditional.
        </p>
        <p>
          Some GCs will ask you to sign an unconditional progress waiver before payment. This
          protects them, but it exposes you to the risk described above. Several states have
          statutes that address this practice — California's Civil Code and Texas's Property Code,
          for example, both contain provisions around lien waivers — but requirements vary. Know
          what the law allows in the project's state before signing, and try to negotiate
          conditional waivers in the subcontract if the GC's template defaults to unconditional.
        </p>
        <p>
          Keeping a clear record of what you billed each period makes waiver management
          straightforward. Having your <a href="/blog/schedule-of-values-guide/"
            >schedule of values</a
          >{' '}
          current and your pay application history organized means you always know exactly what amount
          each waiver should reference — and you can spot a discrepancy before you sign.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="my-10">
