      <div
        class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tight prose-a:text-brand-600"
      >
        <h2>Lien waivers and retainage release</h2>
        <p>
          At project closeout, retainage release is often conditioned on the GC or owner receiving
          signed lien waivers from all subs. This creates a practical exchange: your final{' '}
          <a href="/blog/retainage-construction-guide/">retainage</a> payment and your final lien waiver
          happen at the same time. The conditional final waiver protects you through that exchange — sign
          it before the funds clear and the condition keeps your lien rights intact; once the money is
          confirmed in your account, the waiver takes effect.
        </p>
        <p>
          Know your closeout documents in advance. Most GCs need a final pay application, a
          conditional final lien waiver, and sometimes a closeout certificate or consent of surety.
          Ask what the full closeout package requires before you're in the middle of final billing —
          preparing these documents before the last day of the job is far easier than being the
          holdout while everyone waits on the retainage wire.
        </p>
        <p>
          Also review whether your subcontract includes lower-tier sub flow-down requirements. If
          you've hired sub-subcontractors or suppliers of significant value, the GC may need lien
          waivers from them as well before releasing your retainage. That means you need to collect
          waivers from your own lower-tier subs, not just provide yours.
        </p>

        <h2>State law and statutory forms</h2>
        <p>
          Lien waiver law varies significantly by state. Several states — California, Arizona,
          Texas, Nevada, and others — mandate specific statutory forms, and using a non-compliant
          form can leave the waiver legally ineffective or create grounds for dispute. In those
          states, whatever form the GC sends you should match the statutory language; if it doesn't,
          raise it before signing.
        </p>
        <p>
          In states without mandatory forms, the language in whatever document you sign is what
          governs. Read the scope, the dollar amount, and whether retainage is explicitly excluded
          before signing anything unconditional. "Full and final" or "all claims" language in a
          progress waiver is a red flag — it may be drafted to cover more than the current period.
        </p>
        <p>
          A construction attorney licensed in the project's state is the right resource when you're
          unsure about specific waiver language, particularly on large projects or when a GC is
          pushing for unconditional waivers before payment. The cost of a one-time review is a
          fraction of the lien rights you could be waiving.
        </p>

        <h2>Practical rules for managing lien waivers</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Sign conditional, not unconditional, before payment clears.</strong> This is the single
            most important rule. Conditional waivers protect you if something goes wrong; unconditional
            ones don't.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Verify the amount on every waiver.</strong> The dollar amount should match what you
            billed for that period — not a rounded number, not your full contract sum on a progress waiver.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Confirm retainage is excluded on progress waivers.</strong> A progress waiver should
            carve out withheld retainage explicitly. If it doesn't, you may be waiving rights for money
            you haven't been paid yet.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Keep every signed waiver on file.</strong> Organized by project and billing period,
            your waiver record is part of your payment documentation and your protection if a dispute
            arises later.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>For final waivers, confirm every dollar first.</strong> Wait for the complete final
            payment, including retainage, to clear your account before signing an unconditional final
            waiver.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          Lien waivers are a routine part of construction billing, but they carry real legal weight.
          Understanding what you're signing — and when — keeps the collection process working in
          your favor and protects you when a payment is delayed or disputed.
        </p>
      </div>

